lead_paragraph: The state found itself in a new and unfamiliar role on Tuesday: potential kingmaker at a point when party nominations have usually been sewn up.

byline.contributor: Reporting was contributed by Joseph Berger, Alex Vadukul, Rebecca White and Jason Grant.
byline.original: By MICHAEL BARBARO and NOAH REMNICK

headline.print_headline: Among New York Voters, Primary Day Gets Personal
headline.main: How New York Took Primary Day: Personally

snippet: The state found itself in a new and unfamiliar role on Tuesday: potential kingmaker at a point when party nominations have usually been sewn up.
abstract: Millions of voters turn out for New York's presidential primary as state finds itself in unfamiliar circumstances of potentially deciding outcome at time in campaign cycle when nominations would normally have been already determined and voting almost moot point.
